ities in pursuit of equal rights for Indigenous women and children. After decades of activism and court battles, First Nations women succeeded in changing these oppressive regulations, thus benefitting thousands of their descendants. Those interested in human rights, activism, history, and Indigenous Studies will find that these personal stories, enriched by detailed notes and photographs, form a passionate record of an important, continuing struggle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree womenzCanadavBiography. 0aOral historyzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aIndigenous Studies.  aOral Histories.  aWomen's Studies.1 aCampbell, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoyette, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinhauer, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978177212129240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781772121292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781772121292/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles